	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Short-term global coffee market trends</h1>

			
			<h4>
												06 February 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>At the beginning of 2012, <i>Agrimoney.com</i> reviewed various projections for the short-term future of robusta coffee prices. It noted that robusta prices ‘underperformed in 2011’ with a decline of 15.2%.</p><p>According to analysis from Commerzbank, while production has increased, ‘many producers are waiting for higher prices before selling, and deliveries have therefore lagged behind expectations’. Commerzbank expected ‘average robusta coffee price in 2012 of $1,850 a ton’. They note that currently arabica coffee attracts prices 2.5 times higher than robusta varieties, which is higher than the long-term trend of prices being twice as high. However, according to analysts at Morgan Stanley, demand growth for coffee is slowing, stabilising the arabica–robusta spread ‘at a historically elevated level’.</p><p>According to a December 2011 review, arabica coffee market prices in New York are set for an 8% decline in 2011. This compares to ‘the rise of more than 75% in 2010’. A weaker global economy and a bumper crop for a Brazilian ‘off’ year are seen as the main causes of the arabica price weakening.</p><p>Commerzbank projects arabica coffee prices of above 200 US cents/lb in 2012, a price level that is high by historical standards. High-quality arabica beans in particular are expected to stay in short supply. Overall according to Commerzbank’s analysts, ‘the global coffee market has been in deficit for years, and at best the forthcoming 2012-13 season could end with supply and demand roughly in balance’.</p><p>According to Goldman Sachs, low beginning stocks, slower global production and strong emerging market demand should ‘keep prices elevated’. However, over the medium term a strong supply response to elevated prices is expected, ‘with a large “on-year” harvest in Brazil under average weather conditions’ in the 2012–13 crop year.</p><p>Rabobank analysts meanwhile argue that while ‘the 2011-12 coffee season will be characterised by razor-thin stocks and high risks’, this will be ‘a turning point in a decade-long trend of shrinking supply’.</p><p><b>Forecasts for robusta and Arabica coffee prices in 2012</b></p><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0">
