<p>Source: Compiled by author from press reports.</p><p>Press reports from Jamaica indicate, however, that next year’s coffee crop could be 30% smaller than previous years. Farmers have recently been ‘negatively affected by low farm-gate prices’, particularly for the premium brand Jamaican Blue Mountain (JBM) coffee. As a consequence, the Jamaican Coffee Industry Board has increased prices by around one-third. It has also reviewed payment arrangements in order to improve farmers’ cash flow in the face of rising input costs. The marketing perspective for the current crop, however, is seen as ‘positive’, despite the economic difficulties faced in Japan. Prior to 2009, Japan took some 85% of the JBM crop, with 10% going to the US and Canada, and most of the remainder going to Europe.</p><p>The scope for increasing local processing of JMB coffee is seen as limited, given the high handling, packaging, roasting and marketing costs faced by smaller roasters.</p>
		
		
