<a href="http://www.agrimoney.com/feature/arabica-coffee-prices---what-does-2012-hold--128.html" target="_self">http://www.agrimoney.com/feature/arabica-coffee-prices---what-does-2012-...</a></p><p><i>Jamaica Gleaner</i>, ‘Coffee sales improve’, 23 December 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20111223/business/business4.html" target="_self">http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20111223/business/business4.html</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The increasing price differential between arabica and robusta coffee varieties is indicative of the influence of the growth in production of robusta coffee in Vietnam and the trend towards the more discerning consumption of coffee in both developed and emerging markets.</p><p>Trends in global demand would appear to be opening up opportunities for an expansion of quality-differentiated marketing of arabica coffees from East Africa. However, the recent Jamaican experience in the marketing of Blue Mountain coffee highlights the need for constant innovation in the marketing of premium brand coffees and the importance of maintaining diversified markets, so that sector development strategies are not thrown off course by sudden downturns in particular markets. The Jamaican experience also highlights the need to maintain a close eye on the cash flow situation of farmers to make sure that appropriate seasonal financing arrangements are in place, given escalating inputs costs and the wider credit squeeze (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘Market diversification is key to price premiums for Blue Mountain coffee’, 3 April 2011).</p><p>Experience in Kenya highlights the need for strengthening farmers’ cooperatives to allow both for the cost-effective bulking and processing of coffee, and the development of appropriate risk management strategies to cope with market volatility and market downturns. This is one of the focal activities of the Eastern Africa Fine Coffees Association (EAFCA), which supports capacity building and strong marketing through annual coffee exhibitions. Ensuring that producer bodies can be more proactive in responding to emerging market challenges is likely to be a critical area for policy development in the coming period.</p>
		</div>
		
